5:
Tomorrow we delve into Kaleidoscope.
Have you made preparations?
11: Uh, what exactly do we need?
14:
Why, everything, of course! It's an
ever-shifting labyrinth!
16:
Sure, the shallow levels have been
charted, but the depths are still a
mystery. One can't be too prepared.
20:
R-Right... You've got a point. We'll take it
more seriously!
23: I'm just glad I got through to you in time.
25:
Now then, shall we go shopping?
Here's a list I've prepared.
30:
Wow, how considerate! That's an
adventurer for you!
35:
I-I just figured it would be faster if I did
it myself. That's all!
38:
Right then, let's get a move on! I'll show
you what's useful on an excavation!
43:
When it comes to the shallows, we
already know what we're dealing with.
For example, a desert region will require
sun protect—
48:
What about this? It's called
"Eau de Cherub".
51:
Ooh, it aids with rest! That could be
useful during our camp outs. Is this
what we should be buying?
59:
Fall asleep with a mere whiff.
ight hours of sleep guaranteed—
like sleeping on a cloud.
62:
Deep sleep in a dungeon is out of the
question! And what's even in this?
Perhaps I should report it to the guild...
66:
In any case, we have no use for it.
Put it back where—
73: "365 Ways to Kill a Giant Spider"?
77:
Three-hundred and HOW many!
Someone really hates creepy crawlies!
Who in the world wrote—
82:
H-how dare you! You don't know the
author of this book?!
89:
Lady Levy Gracia! She's only the
embodiment of strength, beauty,
and intelligence for we adventurers!
95:
M-must you? No one needs 365 ways
to kill anything! She just wanted
a snappy title!
99: Hush already! I MUST have this!
103:
Oh man... What's so great about
her books anyway?
108:
Hah. So she's piqued your interest!
Her most famous work is called
"One Single Rule". Here! I'd love for you
to read it!
112:
N-no, I'm fine! I can't believe you carry it
around with you...
116: This is a book for would-be adventurers.
119:
Aren't you already an established
adventurer, Trista?
124:
W-well, yes. But I'm still a long way
away from my goal, I suppose.
127:
...You see, actually, my grandma was
also an adventurer. Just like Lady Levy.
134:
When I was young, she would tell me
stories of her adventures with her
companions in the labyrinth.
They were so cool.
136:
I, too, wanted to take up the explorer's
mantle someday. But I'm still a far cry
from her.
139:
I know very well that there's no point in
buying piles of these books. But it feels
like some kind of progress.
145:
Reading books is a great method for
improving one's abilities. I think that is
quite logical.
152:
Knowledge is beneficial. Therefore
I would also like to read this book.
158:
Yes... Yes, you understand! To gather
knowledge and apply it—THAT is
Lady Levy's one rule!
162: ...So, I think I'll just leave you both to—
165:
I promise you, after I have digested
this tome, we shall test all 365 ways,
again and again, until no spider dares
stand in our path!
170:
Yikes... I hope I don't get swept up in this
weird training...
